<dl id="un1005aa"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="un1" href="#un1005">UN1: </a>  <a href="../../FF/unbs/un1all.htm#un1005aa"> (NLI.3) 5(aa)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Burney (Frances): Evelina, Cecilia</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The most difficult figure to fit in to any progressive scheme of English fiction is <mark>FRANCES BURNEY</mark>, who was actually alive with Samuel Richardson and with Mr. George Meredith. She wrote seldom, and published at long intervals; her best novels, founded on a judicious study of Marivaux and Rousseau, implanted on a strictly British soil, were produced a little earlier than the moment we have now reached. Yet the <cite>Wanderer</cite> was published simultaneously with <cite>Waverley</cite>. She is a social satirist of a very sprightly order, whose early <mark><cite>Evelina</cite></mark> and <mark><cite>Cecilia</cite></mark> were written with an ease which she afterwards unluckily abandoned for an aping of the pomposity of her favourite lexicographer. Miss Burney was a delightful novelist in her youth, but, unless she influenced Miss Austen, she took no part in the progressive development of English literature. <small> Edmund Gosse, <a name="EGSH" href="/udra/udex.htm#EGSH"><cite title="source">A Short History of Modern English Literature</cite></a> (1897), 294f</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Frances (Fanny) Burney (1752-1840), English novelist. </mm> </dd></dl>
